Part 5

The room emptied out slowly, the way rooms do when everyone in them is pretending not to hurry.

Vikram stood at the window after the last chair had scraped back, hands in his pockets, looking down at the city his father's name had built one clumsy signature at a time.

He didn't hear Binay come back in.

"They don't believe you can do it."

Vikram didn't turn.

"I've been doing it for ten years, and nobody in that room noticed."

Binay came to stand beside him, slower than he used to, one hand briefly finding the window frame for balance before he let go of it again, unwilling to be seen needing it.

"That's the wrong complaint."

"What's the right one?"

"The question was never whether they noticed."

A pause, long enough that Vikram finally looked at him.

"The question is whether you'll do it again. Somewhere nobody hands you the ground already prepared. Somewhere you're the kid Reddy thinks you are, because for one honest minute, you actually will be."

Vikram looked back at the glass.

The city lights outside had turned the window into a soft double exposure — the boardroom behind him faintly ghosted over the skyline in front, and somewhere in the overlap, for just a blink, the reflection looking back wasn't a thirty-year-old in a suit.

It was thinner. Younger. A hostel corridor phone still warm against one ear.

He blinked and it was gone, replaced by the version of himself that had learned, over ten patient years, exactly how much a face can be asked to hold without cracking.

"I did it once already," Vikram said, "when I didn't choose it."

"Yes."

"This time I'd be choosing it."

"Yes," Binay said again, and there was something almost like relief in the single word, the sound of a man setting down a question he'd been carrying longer than his son knew.

Neither of them said the rest of it out loud — that "choosing it" this time also meant choosing it without a father in the next room to call if it went wrong, that the ten remaining weeks or months were the last stretch of road where Vikram would ever again get to make a decision with Binay Ahuja still alive to see it land.

Vikram didn't answer with words.

He straightened his jacket, the way he had once straightened a borrowed apron in front of a bathroom mirror before a ragging that turned out to be nothing worth fearing, and found that the promise he was making wasn't really to Reddy, waiting to be proven wrong tomorrow.

It wasn't even to the thin man standing beside him, though he owed him more than either of them would ever say plainly.

It was to a nineteen-year-old who had once left a pathology textbook open on a hostel desk, mid-sentence, and never gotten to finish reading it.

*I'll finish something, for you,* he thought. *Not that. But something.*

"Tell them yes," Vikram said. "South India. All of it."

Binay nodded once, the nod of a man who'd expected this answer and was still glad to hear it out loud.

They stood together at the window a while longer, saying nothing else, the city going on beneath them exactly as it had before either of them decided anything at all.
